SIMPLE: off
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Off
<hw>Off</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧f; 115)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>of</ets>, orig. the same word as R. <ets>of</ets>, prep., AS.
<ets>of</ets>, adv. & prep. ⟦root⟧194. See <er>Of</er>.]</ety> <def>In a
general sense, denoting from or away from; as:</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Denoting distance or separation; <as>as, the house
is a mile <ex>off</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Denoting the action of removing or separating;
separation; <as>as, to take <ex>off</ex> the hat or cloak; to cut
<ex>off</ex>, to pare <ex>off</ex>, to clip <ex>off</ex>, to peel
<ex>off</ex>, to tear <ex>off</ex>, to march <ex>off</ex>, to fly
<ex>off</ex>, and the like.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Denoting a leaving, abandonment, departure,
abatement, interruption, or remission; <as>as, the fever goes
<ex>off</ex>; the pain goes <ex>off</ex>; the game is <ex>off</ex>; all
bets are <ex>off</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Denoting a different direction; not on or towards:
away; <as>as, to look <ex>off</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Denoting opposition or negation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The questions no way touch upon puritanism, either <qex>off</qex>
or on.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Sanderson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>From off</b></col>, <cd>off from; off.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧A live
coal . . . taken with the tongs <xex>from off</xex> the altar.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Is. vi. 6.</au> -- <col><b>Off and on</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Not constantly; not regularly; now and then; occasionally.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>On different tacks, now toward, and
now away from, the land.</cd> -- <col><b>To be off</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To depart; to escape; <as>as, he <ex>was off</ex>
without a moment's warning</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To be abandoned,
as an agreement or purpose; <as>as, the <xex>bet</xex> was declared
<ex>to be off</ex></as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <mcol><col><b>To
come off</b></col>, <col><b>To cut off</b></col>, <col><b>To fall
off</b></col>, <col><b>To go off</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under
<er>Come</er>, <er>Cut</er>, <er>Fall</er>, <er>Go</er>, etc.</cd> --
<col><b>To get off</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To utter; to discharge;
<as>as, <ex>to get off</ex> a joke</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To go
away; to escape; <as>as, <ex>to get off</ex> easily from a
trial</as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <mcol><col><b>To take
off</b></col> <col><b>To do a take-off on</b></col>, <col><b>To take
off</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to mimic, lampoon, or impersonate.</cd> --
<col><b>To tell off</b></col> <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to
divide and practice a regiment or company in the several formations,
preparatory to marching to the general parade for field exercises.</cd>
<au>Farrow.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to rebuke (a person) for an improper
action; to scold; to reprimand.</cd> -- <col><b>To be well
off</b></col>, <cd>to be in good condition.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To be
ill off</b></col>, <col><b>To be badly off</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to be
in poor condition.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 998 --></p>

<p><ent>Off</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Off
<hw>Off</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧f; 115)</pr>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>Away;
begone; -- a command to depart.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Off</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Off
<hw>Off</hw>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>Not on; away from; <as>as, to be
<ex>off</ex> one's legs or <ex>off</ex> the bed; two miles <ex>off</ex>
the shore.</as></def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Off hand</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Offhand</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Off side</b></col> <sd>(Football)</sd>, <cd>out of play; -- said
when a player has got in front of the ball in a scrimmage, or when the
ball has been last touched by one of his own side behind him.</cd> --
<col><b>To be off color</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>to be of a wrong
color.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to be mildly obscene.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>To be off one's food</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To be
off one's feed</b></col></mcol>, (<mark>Colloq.</mark>) <cd>to have no
appetite; to be eating less than usual.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Off</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Off
<hw>Off</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>On the farther side; most
distant; on the side of an animal or a team farthest from the driver
when he is on foot; in the United States, the right side; <as>as, the
<ex>off</ex> horse or ox in a team, in distinction from the
<ant>nigh</ant> or <ant>near</ant> horse or ox; the <ex>off</ex>
leg.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Designating a time when one is not strictly
attentive to business or affairs, or is absent from his post, and,
hence, a time when affairs are not urgent; <as>as, he took an
<ex>off</ex> day for fishing: an <ex>off</ex> year in
politics</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In the <xex>off</xex> season.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Designating a time when one's performance is below
normal; <as>as, he had an <ex>off</ex> day</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Off side</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The right hand side
in driving; the farther side.</cd> See <er>Gee</er>. <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Cricket)</fld> <cd>See <er>Off</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Off</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Off
<hw>Off</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>The side of the
field that is on the right of the wicket keeper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>offal</ent>⟦br⟧
